metadata.name: Whisper #174
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: The Arcade State #21
metadata.description:
"The Arcade State is a strange place.
You can only walk in four directions. Which will it be? 
As you make your way across the landscape, you will discover lush grasslands, grim structures, and colorful grounds. And if you get lucky, you might unearth artifacts of other times, hidden deep inside the system."
   - The Architect -


I am an artist and a scientist fueled by challenges. I'm most creative when I can't work under perfect conditions and I have to improvise to find a solution.
For The Arcade State, I constrained myself to only using four angles along the circle (45, 90, 135, and 180 degrees) while still producing interesting images with depth and variety.


Keys:
Press 'e' to export the image in HD  (1600x2000)
Press 'h' to export the image in UHD (4800x6000) - this will take a few seconds

objkt.name: How much of one is in the other #144

metadata.name: How much of one is in the other #144
metadata.description:
"How much of one is in the other" explores the unique invocations of the RGB colour space. Colour value as defined in applications is a combination of Red, Green and Blue values between the ranges of 0-255. This work generates a unique colour from the hashcode and thus values for each of Red, Green and Blue channels. Each unique minted edition of this work visually explores its RGB colour space by keeping one value constant while the other is circled between 0 to 255 values. The resulting work is a unique rendering of each color value varying between their maximum ranges, by always keeping one value constant. The final image is constructed in a way that it also reads as an aesthetic graph of the minted RGB values.

"How much of one is in the other" is also a conceptual artwork, in a way that the title also encodes the algorithm itself. The idea driving the work emerges from our individualities that creates differentiated notions of self resulting a fragmented world, but yet we are also social beings with our emotions, desires, likes and dislike and such qualities that bind us as human beings. This work attempts to bring to surface these commonalities of our unique selves.

metadata.name: abstraction #118
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

When spring doesn't come soon enough, we can make our own spring. Branch by branch, petal by petal, watch a tree come into being and bloom.

"i": toggle day/night (invert colors).
"p": pause/resume animation.

A tree grows different during the day and at night. You can become a master of time to nurture your own unique tree.

These interactive drawings are made entirely of BÃ©zier curves.
Created by Elsif (ElsifThen@twitter) using p5js.

metadata.name: Schetsboek  #180
metadata.description:
This is my little tribute to fx (hash and fam).

During an important phone call, I was put on hold. Unconsciously, I began to scribble in my sketchbook. Research shows that scribbling helps focusing, but I dreamed away nonetheless until my pages were filled with scribbles, notes, shopping and a to-do list. 

Mint a uniquely generated page from my non-existent 100% coded sketchbook (except text typography). 

The page may contain many scribbles and drawings in pen, felt-tip pen, pencil, or less: often references to artists I admire, some in the form of loose scribbles, others in the form of riddles. Those drawings are drawn with code and vary. Unfortunately, I wasnâ€™t able to incorporate tributes to all art and every artist I admire. The sketchbook would never finish. Thanks to rudxane I know that itâ€™s ok to publish something unfinished ;-). 

One reference that appears in every token is to Sol Lewitt, an incredible source of inspiration. His artworks consist of instructions. Your sketch book pages contain instructions too. You will find the instructions for the artwork scribbled on your unique page by pressing i.

Curious how the work would look without the â€˜distractingâ€™ scribbles and coffee stains? Press â€˜aâ€™, â€˜wâ€™, or â€˜gâ€™. 

800 x 800 px

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save an image.

Made with p5js and the amazing p5.scribble.js library by Janneck Wullschleger.

Font used: Sacremento-Regular under the SIL Open Font License (OFL).

See license.md for the licenses of both.

Thank you all!
